{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633085"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:49:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:49:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17463"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17463"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0.64,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10153"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56301"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5483"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23813"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EResearch papers come in many different formats, each with specific methodological approaches and purposes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key characteristic of a narrative review?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reports original experimental research findings","Uses systematic methods to identify all relevant studies","Provides a broad overview based on expert selection of literature","Presents a single detailed case report","Combines statistical results from multiple studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enarrative review provides a broad overview based on expert selection of literature\u003C/strong\u003E. These reviews summarise and synthesise existing knowledge on a topic, drawing from articles chosen based on the author\u0027s expertise and familiarity with the field. While valuable for education and understanding current perspectives, they lack the rigorous methodology of systematic reviews.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReports original experimental research findings\u003C/strong\u003E describes primary research articles where investigators conduct experiments and present new data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUses systematic methods to identify all relevant studies\u003C/strong\u003E describes systematic reviews which follow strict protocols and explicit methodology for literature searching and selection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresents a single detailed case report\u003C/strong\u003E describes case reports which document the presentation, diagnosis and management of individual clinical cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombines statistical results from multiple studies\u003C/strong\u003E describes meta-analyses which use statistical methods to pool and analyse quantitative data from multiple studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENarrative reviews are particularly useful for educational purposes and providing broad context, but their conclusions may be influenced by selection bias since there is no standardised method for choosing which studies to include.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A narrative review summarises existing literature on a topic using expert knowledge without a systematic search strategy.","Narrative reviews are useful for providing broad overviews but are subject to selection and publication bias.","Unlike systematic reviews, narrative reviews do not require explicit methods for article selection or data extraction."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56301"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17463"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56301"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:26:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:26:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10153"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70834"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{